ing case that the majority of the Iberian plaques were genealogical records of the dead that served as durable markers of regional and local group identities. Such records, she argues, would have contributed toward legitimating and perpetuating an ideology of inherited social difference in the Iberian Late Neolithic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAntiquities, PrehistoriczIberian Peninsula. 0aBurialzIberian Peninsula. 0aNeolithic periodzIberian Peninsula. 0aPlaques, plaquetteszIberian Peninsula. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aWoods, Alexander P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/71822740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292794184423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292794184/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK